				<b class="paperTitle"><a href="https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-030-63086-7_10" target="_blank">The Bitcoin Hunter: Detecting Bitcoin Traffic Over Encrypted Channels</a></b> <br>
				<span class="paperAuthor">&nbsp;  Fatemeh Rezaei, Shahrzad Naseri,  <b>Amir Houmansadr</b>, and  Ittay Eyal<br>
					&nbsp; <i><b>SecureComm</b></i>  2020 <br></span>
					<div id="securecomm20_collapsed"
					style="display: block; color: black;" align="justify"><a
					href="javascript:swap('securecomm20')"
					style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">[+] <i>Abstract</i>
				</a> </div>
				<div id="securecomm20_expanded" style="display: none;"
				align="justify"> <a href="javascript:swap('securecomm20')"
				style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">[-] <i><u>Abstract:</u></i> </a> <span class="indented">
					Bitcoin and similar blockchain-based currencies are signifi- cantly important to consumers and industry because of their applica- tions in electronic commerce and other trust-based distributed systems. Therefore, it is of paramount importance to the consumers and industry to maintain reliable access to their Bitcoin assets. In this paper, we inves- tigate the resilience of Bitcoin to blocking by powerful network entities such as ISPs and governments. By characterizing Bitcoin’s communica- tion patterns, we design classifiers that can distinguish (and therefore block) Bitcoin traffic even if tunneled through an encrypted channel like Tor, and even if mixed with background traffic (e.g., due to open web- browser tabs). We also evaluate the reliability of our bitcoin detectors in the presence of traffic obfuscation tools like Tor pluggable transports, showing that such obfuscation mechanisms are not enough to ensure blocking-resistant access to Bitcoin, therefore arguing for traffic obfus- cation mechanisms that are tailored to cryptocurrency applications.

				</span><br>
