<b class="paperTitle"><a href="papers/PETS17-TagIt.pdf" target="_blank">TagIt: Tagging Network Flows using Blind Fingerprints</a></b> <br>
<span class="paperAuthor">&nbsp;  <a href="">Fatemeh Rezaei</a> and <b>Amir Houmansadr</b><br>
	&nbsp; <i><b>PETS</b></i>  2017 <br></span>
	<div id="PETs17_collapsed"
	style="display: block; color: black;" align="justify"><a
	href="javascript:swap('PETs17')"
	style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">[+] <i>Abstract</i>
</a> </div>
<div id="PETs17_expanded" style="display: none;"
align="justify"> <a href="javascript:swap('PETs17')"
style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">[-] <i><u>Abstract:</u></i> </a> <span class="indented">
	Flow fingerprinting is a mechanism for linking
	obfuscated network flows at large scale. In this paper,
	we introduce the first blind flow fingerprinting system
	called TagIt. Our system works by modulating fingerprint
	signals into the timing patterns of network flows
	through slightly delaying packets into secret time intervals
	only known to the fingerprinting parties. We design
	TagIt to to enable reliable fingerprint extraction by legitimate
	fingerprinting parties despite natural network
	noise, but invisible to an adversary who does not possess
	the secret fingerprinting key. TagIt makes use of
	randomization to resist various detection attacks such as
	multi-flow attacks. We evaluate the performance and invisibility
	of TagIt through theoretical analysis as well as
	simulations and experimentation on live network flows.<br>
</span>
</div>
