<b class="paperTitle"><a href="papers/isita16.pdf" target="_blank">Achieving Perfect Location Privacy in Markov Models Using Anonymization</a></b> <br>
<span class="paperAuthor">&nbsp;  <a href="">Zarrin Montazeri</a>, <b>Amir Houmansadr</b>, and <a href="http://www.ecs.umass.edu/ece/pishro/" target="_blank">Hossein Pishro-Nik</a><br>
	&nbsp; <i><b>ISITA</b></i>  2016 <br></span>
	<div id="ISITA_collapsed"
	style="display: block; color: black;" align="justify"><a
	href="javascript:swap('ISITA')"
	style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">[+] <i>Abstract</i>
</a> </div>
<div id="ISITA_expanded" style="display: none;"
align="justify"> <a href="javascript:swap('ISITA')"
style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">[-] <i><u>Abstract:</u></i> </a> <span class="indented">

	Our previous work [1] defined the notion of perfect location privacy for
	location-based services (LBS) and demonstrated how it can be achieved
	under basic user models.
	In this paper, we extend our work by studying perfect location privacy within
	a more complex scenario in which
	a user's movements are dependent upon the time domain.
	We model a mobile user's path using Markov chains
	and show that perfect location privacy is achievable for the user
	if her pseudonym is changed before $O\Big(n^{\frac{2}{|E|-r}}\Big)$ observations
	by the adversary, where $|E|$ is the number of edges in the Markov model
	and $r$ is the number of all possible locations.
	We support our results with simulations.
</span><br>
</div>
